CHEYENNE LIGHT, FUEL AND POWER 40 MW SALE TO BASIN ELECTRIC CONFIRMATION AGREEMENT
This Confirmation Agreement ("Agreement"), dated March 11, 2013, is by and between Basin Electric Power Cooperative ("Basin Electric") and Cheyenne Light, Fuel and Power Company, ("CLFP"), collectively the "Parties" on the terms and conditions stated below:
WHEREAS, prior to the Start Date the Parties will be members of Western System Power Pool ("WSPP") and parties to the latest WSPP Agreement ("Governing Agreement"); and
WHEREAS, the Parties desire to enter into a transaction for the purchase and sale of firm electric power and energy pursuant to Schedule C of the Governing Agreement, except as modified by this Confirmation Agreement. In the case of an actual or perceived conflict between the terms of this Confirmation Agreement and the terms of Schedule C or any other provision of the Governing Agreement, the terms stated in this Confirmation Agreement shall control.
NOW THEREFORE, the parties do hereby agree as follows:
Buyer: Basin Electric Power Cooperative
Seller: Cheyenne Light, Fuel and Power Company
Buyer Scheduling Agent: Western Area Power Administration's Energy Management and Marketing Office ("EMMO") located at Montrose, Colorado, shall serve as Basin Electric's Scheduling Agent. Business Phone is: Pre-schedule 970 252-3013 Real-time 800 378-6453 Seller Scheduling Agent: Black Hills Power ("BHP") located at Rapid City, South Dakota, shall serve as CLFP's Scheduling Agent. Business Phone is: Pre-schedule 605 716-3901 Real-time 605 721-2267 Governing Agreement: Western Systems Power Pool Agreement, as amended.
Service: WSPP Service Schedule C - Firm Capacity/Energy Sale or Exchange Service Basin Electric shall purchase and take delivery of the Contract Amount capacity and energy from CLFP at the Delivery Point.
Contract Amount: 40 MW
FERC Acceptance: Each Party's obligations under this Agreement are expressly contingent on acceptance of this Agreement and the Concurrent Confirmation for filing by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC")(acceptance of this agreement and the Concurrent Confirmation shall be collectively referred to herein as "FERC Acceptance"). CLFP will submit those agreements to FERC for approval no later than five (5) days after the execution and delivery thereof by the parties and will notify Basin Electric within five (5) business days after FERC Acceptance. In the event that FERC Acceptance is not granted within sixty (60) business days of the execution and delivery of the agreements by the parties, either party shall have the option, upon written notice to the other party, to terminate both this Agreement and the Concurrent Confirmation. In the event FERC does not accept either of those agreements, both agreements shall automatically terminate without further action by either Party. In either event of termination described above, neither Party shall have any further liability or obligation to the other Party hereunder.
Term: START DATE: Hour Ending ("HE") 0100 Mountain Prevailing Time (MPT) on the later of April 1, 2013 or the date of FERC acceptance.
END DATE: HE 2400 MPT on September 30, 2014.
Energy Price:
Term On-Peak ($/MWh) Off Peak ($/MWh)
START DATE - END DATE Delivery of 40 MW @ Stegall West bus
$33.50 /MWh
$23.50 /MWh
On Peak is defined as the period Hour Ending ("HE") 0800 - HE 2300, MPT, Monday through Saturday (6X16), excluding all NERC defined holidays. Off peak is defined as all other hours.
Delivery Point: CLFP shall deliver the Contract Amount to Basin Electric for the Term at the Stegall West (SGW) and shall maintain firm transmission service at its own expense to SGW. CLFP alternatively shall deliver the Contract Amount to other points as directed by Basin as prescheduled by Basin Electric as located on the Black Hills/Basin Electric Common Use interconnected transmission system (BHBE); provided, however, that all firm BHBE delivery points other than SGW will be on an as available basis.
Scheduling: Basin Electric shall purchase and schedule and CLFP shall sell and deliver, the Contract Amount of firm power and energy during the Term at the Delivery Point. Basin Electric shall submit its energy schedule to CLFP's Scheduling Agent in accordance with the then current Western Electrical Coordinating Council and Western Area Colorado Missouri scheduling dates. Basin Electric shall be responsible for all applicable North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) tagging requirements.
Damages for Default: The full Contact Amount of power and energy associated with this Confirmation Agreement is considered firm and not recallable for any reason. In the event that either party fails to perform its respective obligations under this Confirmation Agreement to sell and deliver or to take and pay for the full Contract Amount for any reason amounting to a breach of its obligations hereunder, Parties will settle damages by application of the damage calculations stated in subsection 21.3 of the Governing Agreement as the non-breaching party's sole and exclusive remedy unless the parties mutually agree otherwise. Basin shall be obligated to pay damages to CLFP if delivery of power and energy by CLFP to points other than SGW (at Basin Electric's direction) is curtailed due to transmission service being non-firm.
Cross Default: This Confirmation Agreement is executed in conjunction with a concurrent agreement ("Concurrent Confirmation") under Service Schedule C of the Governing Agreement under which Basin Electric will deliver 40 MW of firm power and energy to CLFP. Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary, to the extent either Party defaults under the Concurrent Confirmation, such default shall also operate as a default under this Confirmation Agreement.
Invoice and Payment: Unless otherwise agreed, bills for capacity and energy provided under this Agreement shall be rendered by the tenth working day of each month for capacity and energy provided during the previous calendar month. Basin Electric's payment to CLFP in immediately available funds shall be due to CLFP no later than 15 days following the date of receipt of such invoice. Wire transfer shall accomplish payment within the fifteen (15) day period. Payment received subsequent to this due date shall be subject to a prorated annual interest charge equal to the JP Morgan Chase Bank, or its successor's prime rate plus two (2) percent, applied to late payments on a daily basis, on a three hundred and sixty-five (365) day year. If the due date falls on a weekend or a recognized holiday, the due date shall be the next business day.
Adequate Assurance and Creditworthiness: In the event that at any time during the term of this Agreement:
(i) CLFP's senior unsecured rating by either Moody's or Standard & Poor's falls below investment grade, or (ii) if not rated and CLFP's Debt Service Coverage Ratio is less than 1.5,
an unconditional and irrevocable letter of credit in the amount of $500,000 will be required in order to provide adequate assurance to Basin Electric. Such irrevocable letter of credit must be issued in a format and by a bank reasonably acceptable to Basin Electric. Other alternative forms of eligible security may be used by mutual agreement of both Parties. Basin Electric shall return all outstanding security to CLFP upon an upgrade to investment grade or an increase in the Debt Service Coverage Ratio to greater than or equal to 1.5. As used in this Agreement, Debt Service Coverage Ratio shall be calculated by dividing the sum of Net Income, Interest Expense, Depreciation Expense and Amortization Expense by the sum of Interest Expense and Principal Payments and shall be computed based upon the most recent quarterly financial information. Principal Payments shall not include any prepayments or call of existing debt prior to maturity. CLFP shall provide to Basin Electric with the necessary financial information components to enable such computation to be made within 60 days of the end of each quarter.
In the event that at any time during the term of this Agreement Basin Electric's senior unsecured rating by either Moody's or Standard & Poor's falls below investment grade, an unconditional and irrevocable letter of credit in the amount of $500,000 will be required in order to provide adequate assurance to CLFP. Such irrevocable letter of credit must be issued in a format and by a bank reasonably acceptable to CLFP. Other alternative forms of eligible security may be used by mutual agreement of both Parties. CLFP shall return all outstanding security to Basin Electric upon an upgrade to investment grade.
The posting of a single $500,000 letter of credit as contemplated herein shall concurrently satisfy a Parties' obligation under both this Agreement and the Concurrent Confirmation.
Netting: If the Buyer and Seller are each required to pay an amount on the payment due date in the same month for transactions under the Governing Agreement and confirmation(s) there under (including, but not limited to this Confirmation Agreement and the Concurrent Confirmation), then such amounts with respect to each Party will be aggregated and the Parties will discharge their obligations to pay through netting, in which case the Party owing the greater aggregate amount will pay to the other Party the difference between the amounts owed consistent with the payment terms hereunder. Each Party reserves to itself all rights, set-offs, counterclaims and other remedies and/or defenses to which it is or may be entitled, arising from or out of the Confirmation Agreement. All outstanding payments between the Parties which are to be netted shall be offset against each other or set off or recouped there from.
Assignment: The rights and obligations created by this Confirmation Agreement shall inure to the benefit of, and be binding on the successors and assigns of the respective Parties hereto, provided, however that neither Party shall be permitted to assign its rights and obligations under this Agreement without the prior written consent of the other Party which will not be unreasonably withheld.
Contact: BEPC - Jason Doerr @ 701 223-0441
BHP - Andy Butcher @ 605 721-2260
Confidentiality: Neither Party shall disclose the terms and provisions of this Agreement, except to the extent required to in order to satisfy the Conditions Precedent or except to its representatives who have a need to know, or to the extent required in any regulatory proceeding; provided, that if a Party is required by law to make such a disclosure, it shall first notify the other Party, and shall use commercially reasonable efforts to attempt, at its own expense, to restrict or prevent such disclosure, and shall allow the other Party to participate in such attempt, should it choose to do so.
Governing Terms: Capitalized terms used but not defined herein shall have the meanings ascribed to them in the Governing Agreement. To the extent the provisions of this Agreement are in conflict with the Governing Agreement, the provisions of this Agreement shall control.

record_data.record_plain_text:
1. Availability. Seller may make electric capacity, energy, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale.
2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of capacity, energy, or ancillary services by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule.
3. Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions of sales shall be established by agreement between purchaser and Seller.
5. Ancillary Services. Seller may make available to any purchaser the following ancillary services:
a. California ISO Region: Seller may offer regulation service, spinning reserve service, non-spinning reserve service, and contingency reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
b. New York Region: Seller may offer regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
c. New England Region: Seller may offer regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
d. PJM Region: Seller may offer regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
e. Third-Party Provider: Seller offers third-party ancillary services, including Regulation and Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
6. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff.
7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. Seller has received (i) waiver of the accounting and reporting requirements contained in 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101, and 141, except for sections 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subparts B and C, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; and (iii) blanket authorization for the issuance of securities and the assumption of liabilities. See Cheyenne Light, Fuel and Power Company, Letter Order in Docket No. ER08-401-000 (February 26, 2008).
8. Effective Date. This tariff is effective on the date specified by the Commission.
9. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Northwest Region, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a). Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Central, Northeast, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool Regions, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a).
